        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aim at resolving and exploring the structure of an unexpected off-center
Sunyaev-Zeldovich peak in the exceptionally luminous cool core of a
dynamically relaxed galaxy cluster RXCJ1504, discovered in our 12"
resolution 99 GHz CARMA-15 image (Fig. 3a). Our CARMA-8 image, which maps
larger angular scales with a 44" resolution, shows no offset of the global
SZ peak from the X-ray centroid. This points to the presence of a
small-scale gas pressure structure in the core that's not apparent in the
Chandra high-resolution X-ray image, in addition to some more exotic
possibilities.

The area occupied by the CARMA peak is ~20" in diameter. The most compact
ALMA 12m Array configuration in Band 3 provides a field of view of ~1' and a
synthesized beam of 4", 3 times higher than our CARMA image -- enough to
resolve the peak well, but not too fine to resolve away most of the signal
if the peak turns out to be smooth. The maximum recoverable scale that can
be imaged is ~28", which matches our SZ peak size very well. Thus, no
complementary ACA observations are needed to map the peak (for structures on
larger scales, including the 90"-diameter cool core, we have deep CARMA-15
and CARMA-8 data). Furthermore, our SZ peak is contained within the inner
1/3 of the primary beam, so no significant sensitivity loss is expected in
this region.

We used the web-based ALMA Observation Support Tool (OST) to simulate an
ALMA 12m observation in Band 3 with a 4.5" resolution, dual polarization, a
total bandwidth of 7.5 GHz per polarization, default spectral window
frequencies (using 92.5 GHz as representative frequency) and PWV=0.5 mm.
Different on-source times were considered to evaluate the sensitivity needed
to detect and map the CARMA peak area with useful significance. The output
of one of the simulations is shown in Fig. 3b. It is clear from the figure
that the region occupied by the CARMA peak is fully recovered in the
simulated map. The predicted peak value is -68 microJy/beam, which is factor
~1.4 smaller than that expected from a simple scaling of the CARMA peak by
the ratio of the beam areas. This is due to a mild suppression of the
larger-scale signal by ALMA.

To map the structure of the SZ peak with an interesting accuracy requires a
noise level of 10 microJy/beam. The brightest area of the peak (within the
-40 microJy contour in Fig. 3b) will be resolved with ~2x3 ALMA beams; we
aim at detecting brightness variations by factor ~2 between the adjacent
beams at a ~2 sigma significance in order to see if the peak has any
small-scale structure or elongation. For this, a S/N of at least ~5 per beam
is needed. A sensitivity of 10 microJy will allow us to detect the peak flux
at more than 6 sigma and the signal outside the brightest spot at &gt;2 sigma.

According to the ALMA sensitivity calculator, a noise of 10 microJy/beam for
our desired setup will be achieved in 1.7 hr on-source time. As instructed
by the OST help documentation, we base our requested exposure on the ASC
noise estimate (rather than the image simulator, which predicted a slightly
lower noise).

As we did for the CARMA-15 data, we will use the long baselines to measure
the flux density of the ~7 mJy (positive) point source associated with the
central galaxy (marked by a cross in Fig. 3b) and subtract it from the uv
data to obtain a detailed map of the SZ effect alone. It will not pose a
problem for our SZ mapping.

To summarize, we request a single-pointing, continuum observation in Band 3
(7.5 GHz bandwidt, split into the 4 default spectral window frequencies)
with the 4.5" resolution and 10 microJy sensitivity, which can be achieved
with a total on-source time of 1.7 hr (3.4 hr, including calibration time
and total overheads).</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
